35
00:02:01,759 --> 00:02:03,920
And this is when I start spiraling.

36
00:02:03,920 --> 00:02:08,479
The uncertainty, the self-doubt, and then the imposttor syndrome.

37
00:02:08,479 --> 00:02:12,720
All of a sudden, I'm doomcrolling social media, comparing myself to all my competitors.

38
00:02:12,720 --> 00:02:13,920
And then I look up again.

39
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:14,720
It's 8:00 p.m.

40
00:02:14,720 --> 00:02:17,840
and Bernie is barking at me because I still haven't taken him on a walk.

41
00:02:17,840 --> 00:02:19,280
This is not productivity.

42
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:21,599
This is not a good place to be.

43
00:02:21,599 --> 00:02:26,800
There's something wrong with my routine or workflow, but I'm not really sure what it is,

44
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:30,560
but it's late and I got to go to bed.

45
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:33,120
I wake up the next morning with a clearer head.

46
00:02:33,120 --> 00:02:36,640
I fire up Chat GBT looking for a solution this time.

47
00:02:36,640 --> 00:02:38,879
Hey chat, will you be my startup coach?

48
00:02:38,879 --> 00:02:39,280
Sure.

49
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:40,239
What's going on?

50
00:02:40,239 --> 00:02:41,920
I explained the whole situation.

51
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:44,080
Chat, I just feel overwhelmed.

52
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:46,959
Young Patrick, the answer is simple.

53
00:02:46,959 --> 00:02:49,280
You must talk to users.

54
00:02:49,280 --> 00:02:49,840
Why?

55
00:02:49,840 --> 00:02:55,040
Talking to users will help you uncover what they actually struggle with instead of guessing what features they need.

56
00:02:55,040 --> 00:03:02,159
And users will tell you how they describe their problems, which will help you write better copy for your landing page and pitch your product idea more clearly.

57
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:06,879
If you have these regular conversations, they'll help you ship, test, and iterate quickly,

58
00:03:06,879 --> 00:03:09,840
which is the key to actually building something that works.

59
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:13,040
And then it hits me, oh, duh.

60
00:03:13,040 --> 00:03:18,159
All these features I've been building, they're worthless if I don't even know if anybody wants them.

61
00:03:18,159 --> 00:03:19,360
So, here's what I do.

62
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:20,720
I pull up Gmail.

63
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:25,360
I start crafting up a draft to anybody who even signed up for my app.

64
00:03:25,360 --> 00:03:29,360
It says, "Hey there, you're getting this email because you're an early user of Mo.

65
00:03:29,360 --> 00:03:33,440
I know the app is early and it has issues, but thank you for being an early part of it.

66
00:03:33,440 --> 00:03:35,840
Then I told them about new features that we launched.

67
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:39,360
And at the end, I added a line that says, I want to chat with you.

68
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:41,760
I put a link to book something on my calendar.

69
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:43,360
And then I sent it off.

70
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:46,560
Within 2 minutes, I had a call booked on my calendar.

71
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:47,599
Oh my god, what?

72
00:03:47,599 --> 00:03:48,799
This is crazy.

73
00:03:48,799 --> 00:03:50,239
I'm already nervous for this call.

74
00:03:50,239 --> 00:03:53,360
And you probably won't believe this, but I'm actually an introvert.

75
00:03:53,360 --> 00:03:56,640
I just want to sit behind my computer all day and play with Claude Code.

76
00:03:56,640 --> 00:04:00,239
And all day I'm anticipating this meeting with nervous energy.

77
00:04:00,239 --> 00:04:02,879
And then finally the call starts.

78
00:04:02,879 --> 00:04:04,159
I'm waiting.

79
00:04:04,159 --> 00:04:05,360
Nobody's coming on.

80
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:06,720
This guy is going to noshow.

81
00:04:06,720 --> 00:04:09,360
And then all of a sudden a boo joins the call.

82
00:04:09,360 --> 00:04:11,840
A software engineer from South Africa.

83
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:13,040
I'm feeling awkward.

84
00:04:13,040 --> 00:04:14,000
What do I say?

85
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:15,200
But I keep it casual.

86
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:16,799
And I ask him what he does.

87
00:04:16,799 --> 00:04:17,519
Where's he from?

88
00:04:17,519 --> 00:04:20,720
And then all of a sudden he tells me he loves what I'm building.

89
00:04:20,720 --> 00:04:22,079
He loves my app.

90
00:04:22,079 --> 00:04:23,759
I couldn't believe what he was saying.

91
00:04:23,759 --> 00:04:26,479
this thing, this app I'm building is borderline broken.

92
00:04:26,479 --> 00:04:32,080
It's super early, but he tells me he sees the vision and he shows me tweets that he's already created with the app.

93
00:04:32,080 --> 00:04:36,160
We chop it up for almost an hour and he tells me about his app he's building, PRD pulse,

94
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:39,840
and how he's trying to build in public and get out of his introverted shell as well.

95
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:46,080
I ask Abu all sorts of questions that I got from this awesome video by Eric Mijikowski on how to talk to users,

96
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:48,479
and I'll put those in the comments if you want to see them.

97
00:04:48,479 --> 00:04:53,680
At first, before the call started, I was nervous and it felt awkward, but by the end,

98
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:58,800
I realized that he's just another guy like me, a software engineer trying to build his own things and ship them.

99
00:04:58,800 --> 00:04:59,600
It was so much fun.

100
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:04,240
It was so cool meeting one of my users, and it felt amazing after I got off the call.

101
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:08,720
But more importantly than any of that, I got off the call with a renewed sense of clarity.

102
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:16,400
This one quick conversation with my target customer felt more productive than all the features I had been building in the last few weeks.

103
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:19,280
I now knew exactly what my product needed.

104
00:05:19,280 --> 00:05:21,520
I knew exactly who my target customer was.

105
00:05:21,520 --> 00:05:28,080
And I just had so much clarity, which gave me even more conviction about how this idea can be huge.

106
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:33,919
So, I know all I got to do is keep doing this, talking to customers, building what they want,

107
00:05:33,919 --> 00:05:35,280
and talking to customers again.

108
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:38,400
So, what's my big takeaway this week for the 100K build challenge?

109
00:05:38,400 --> 00:05:39,919
Stop hiding behind your code.

110
00:05:39,919 --> 00:05:41,840
Talk to your customers.

111
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:43,360
It doesn't have to be over a call.

112
00:05:43,360 --> 00:05:47,680
It could be an email, a Twitter DM, or even in these YouTube comments right now.

113
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:54,160
One customer conversation might be worth hundreds of hours of coding, and it honestly could make all the difference.

114
00:05:54,160 --> 00:05:56,400
Thank you guys for watching the 100K build challenge.

115
